defaultWritten evidence submitted by David defaultElsteindefault [FBB0104]default&#xa0;
defaultHearings on BBC January 14 2014
defaultI want to cover four topics this morning: governance, culture, scope and funding.
defaultHowever, I want to preface my remarks with an acknowledgement. Most of us – either giving evidence to this committee or perhaps serving on it – believe that the BBC can be improved. But 
defaultin the absence of unanimity as to what to do or how to do it, it is in
defaultcumbent on us to recognize that the BBC works reasonably well, and that most changes to the way it is organised and operated would make only a marginal difference. 
defaultWe tend to take the BBC for granted, yet the sheer scale of its achievements in the nine de
defaultcades of its existence must command our respect. It is by far the major source of news for UK citizens (as well as for many millions beyond Britain), it is our leading cultural institution, it is a key provider of information, educational material and ente
defaultrtainment, and it has created an unrivalled archive of content of great permanent value. 
defaultThat the BBC has survived major
default upheavals, dismissals of leading executives and intermittent changes in structure suggests that it matters little which actual people 
defaultare running the organisation: the thousands of dedicated professionals working within the BBC, and their core commitment to its inherited values, ensure that the many benefits the BBC delivers to us are largely immune to surface turmoil.
