defaultGovernance
defaultThat sa
defaultid
default,
default I have no doubt that the governance system set up at the last Charter review could be improved. The confusion as to who is in control of the BBC’s finances was amply demonstrated by the lamentable public 
defaulthumiliation of past and present members of the B
defaultBC Trust and BBC Executive Board at the September 9
defaultth
default session of the Public Accounts Committee.
defaultPoor communication, ambiguity in relationships, and lack of clarity as to responsibilities were all on display that day. In truth, the argument between the two 
defaultsides was relatively minor – had a few million pounds worth of extra-contractual payments to departing executives been approved properly or not? – 
defaultbut
default the degree of mutual exasperation expressed betrayed structural problems, not just personal ones (as the 
defaultPAC chair tellingly noted).
defaultReplacing the old BBC Governors with the BBC Trust, and allowing the Director-General to chair his own Executive Board (something that would never be tolerated in the commercial world), left the so-called oversight body under-in
defaultformed and too far from the action, whilst allowing too much scope to a single executive. The governance structure at Channel Four seems substantially preferable: a combined board of executives and non-executives, in equal numbers, but with non-executives 
defaultin the roles of chair and deputy chair.
defaultLike all other UK-licensed broadcasters, Channel 4 is regulated by Ofcom, which also regulates some activities of the BBC. It seems to me that there would be significant benefit in 
defaultallowing Ofcom further scope in reg
defaultulating the BBC, most notably in judging complaints about impartiality (it already judges complaints on all other content matters) and monitoring the BBC’s fair trading obligations.
defaultIt is frustrating for viewers and listeners to find that for a single prog
defaultramme broadcast by the BBC, they might need to complain to two different regulators – for instance, to Ofcom on fairness and the BBC Trust on impartiality. It also seems wasteful to ignore Ofcom’s accumulated expertise in judging content issues in favour o
defaultf allowing the Trust to persist with certain matters. In terms of rigged competitions and misuse of premium rate telephone calls, Ofcom proved more astute and rigorous than the Trust in assessing identical material. 
