defaultScope
defaultTwo of the most senior figures working in BBC journalism – David Dimbleby and the recently departed Director of News, 
defaultRoger Mosey – have both recently suggested that the BBC may be too large for its own good (and ours).
defaultTheir remarks have been construed as calling for a reduction in the number of BBC TV channels, or some other curtailment of scope, which has earned a cert
defaultain level of support from some of the BBC’s competitors, most notably the commercial radio companies.
defaultThis is not a new debate. The launch of new domestic TV channels has been subjected to considerable ministerial scrutiny, to limit – if not entirely preve
defaultnt – impact on existing players. Executives at Channel 4 were heard to remark that if the launch of BBC3 was designed to attract more young adults to television, it would make mor
defaulte sense to hand the new channel’s budget
default to Channel 4, 
defaultwhich had an establish
defaulted track record in appealing to those viewers.
defaultLikewise, a proposal to launch local TV stations was vetoed by the BBC Trust, which has also imposed limits on the extent of the BBC’s online activities. Yet the BBC’s ability to flex its muscles, even within 
defaultthe constraints imposed by the Trust and by ministers, inevitably causes problems, as the commercial radio sector regularly complains.
defaultDoes the BBC have too many channels? In truth, with BBC 3 and BBC 4 only available in the evenings, and with BBC2 
defaultconfined to repeats in daytime – other than when it is offering live broadcasts – the scale of the BBC’s television offerings is more show than substance. Indeed, when Lord Hall launches a +1 service for BBC1, he will further enlarge the nominal number of 
defaulthours of transmission, without delivering a single additional programme. Yet the appearance of growing scope and scale can in itself be dangerous, especially when there is a real and serious issue in a key area.
defaultThat area is news consumption. I have raised
default this point with the parallel committee in another place, so I will not re-run all the numbers. The fact is that the BBC is re
defaultsponsible for over 60% of all news consumption by UK adults, a figure that edges higher year by year, as newspaper readership decl
defaultines and TV news consumption shifts steadily away from ITV and towards the BBC. It is likely that by the end of the decade the BBC will account for more than twice as much news consumption as all other sources combined.
defaultThere are many reasons for this phen
defaultomenon, including the declining emphasis placed on news by the BBC’s TV competitors. As the BBC correctly points out, it
default is responsible for barely one quarter
default of all 
defaultTV news
default hours actually broadcast, but nearly three quarters of all TV news viewed: there is clearly consumer preference at work.
defaultOfcom has acknowledged that BBC dominance is a serious issue affecting news plurality in the UK. It has called on the Trust to make in
defaultternal plurality a priority, but received no response. I have described to their Lordships how such plurality might be accomplished, but – again – there appears to be little interest within the BBC.
