defaultFunding
defaultCorrecting the faults I have described in the fir
defaultst three topics would entail very little actual change in the BBC, in terms of operations and structure. However, I have long been an advocate of a more direct funding mechanism for the BBC than the licence fee, in the shape of voluntary subscription, the 
defaultadoption of which would indeed have a major impact on the way the BBC operated.
defaultThe change
defaults I foresee are
default that 
defaultthe BBC television offering would become
default 
defaultmore varied, with viewers offered a choice of channels and packages; that this would create an incentive
default for the BBC to offer more “premium” product, such as high-cost drama, sport, arts and documentaries, so as to tap into the well-established audience demand for these categories; that subscribing would be entirely voluntary, but that a subscriber would nee
defaultd to enable each TV set separately, thereby enlarging the BBC’s total number of licensed units whilst allowing the unit price of a single-set subscription to the current suite of BBC channels to be reduced.
defaultUnder this scenario, the BBC would become directl
defaulty accountable to its subscribers – it might even adopt some form of mutual or membership structure; it would cease to be dependent on politicians to set its income; it could borrow more readily in the debt markets and so invest more heavily in its commerci
defaultal ventures; its reach would decline somewhat, perhaps by 10-
default20%, but its income would rise; the VAT generated from its subscriber charges might be used to launch a contestable public service content fund; it would still be required to spend 20% of its inc
defaultome on free-to-air radio services; and it would undergo a significant shift of its programming priorities away from sheer volume towards higher quality.
defaultI have separately submitted to the Committee a chapter in a forthcoming book dealing with the licence f
defaultee issue, so I will not add to the reading burden by replicating that discussion. However, I would only mention one piece of evidence submitted by the BBC, to the effect that, since 2004, public preference appears to have shifted away from subscription tow
defaultards the licence fee
default.
defaultOf course, 2004 was the last time subscription was widely discussed as an option for the BBC, in the run up to the last Charter review. The Broadcasting Policy Group booklet “Beyond 
defaultThe
default Charter” set out the argument at length. The com
defaultmittee chaired by Lord Burns, set up by Secretary of State Tessa Jowell, also recommended shifting from the licence towards subscription as the best way of funding the BBC. I personally participated in a live Panorama programme that year where the studio a
defaultudience clearly opted for subscription (the case for the licence fee was made by the acting Director-General).
defaultSince then, of course, there has been almost complete silence about any alternative to the licence fee, not least on the BBC, which – see above –
default is responsible for such a vast share of UK news consumption. Instead, the BBC has devoted itself to making the arguments for the licence fee, good and bad. I am, therefore, not much impressed by the research cited, and am confident that a properly conduct
defaulted public debate would result in a very different outcome.
